= Introduction

The vast majority of flowering plant species are pollinated by animals @Ollerton2011HowMan. Pollination interactions are essential to plant reproduction and to the maintenance of Earth’s biodiversity @Bascompte2007PlaMut, yet they are increasingly disrupted by climate and land use change. These forces threaten the structure and functioning of pollination networks @Kearns1998EndMut, as well as the biodiversity and ecosystem services that depend on them, which have been well documented across the globe @Potts2016AssessmentReport. Understanding and predicting how plant-pollinator networks respond to anthropogenic change is a central challenge in pollinator ecology @Mayer2011PolEco and conservation biology @Kearns1998EndMut @Gilman2010FrameworkCommunity, with direct relevance for climate adaptation and food security @Bailes2015HowCana @Klein2006ImpPol.

Alpine ecosystems face a unique combination of threats in this context. As temperatures rise, many plant and pollinator species see their suitable habitat shifting upward along elevational gradients  @Hoiss2015IntEff @Richman2020AsyRan. These shifts can reduce the total amount of climatically viable habitat and tend to particularly threaten high elevation species @Rumpf2018RanDyn. Simulatenously, species phenologies are changing in response to warming and earlier snowmelt @Inouye2020EffectsClimate @Steltzer2009BiologicalConsequences, creating the potential for mismatches in flowering and pollinator activity @Memmott2007GloWar @CaraDonna2014ShiFlo @Ogilvie2017IntBee. While phenological mismatches have received substantial attention, they represent only one component of climate driven disruption. A critical, but less explored challenge is the potential for spatial mismatch among species @Polce2014ClimatedrivenSpatial @Hegland2009HowDoes. As ranges shift, some plant and pollinators may cease to overlap in space, while others co-occur for the first time, producing network rewiring across space. Forecasting how range shifts will reshape communities is crucial for informing conservation decisions @Bates2025PredictionsFuture. Interactions are a crucial component of how climate warming will impact range dynamics @HilleRisLambers2013HowWill, but we cannot adaquetely account for their role in range shifts without clear understanding of the spatial structure of networks.

A major challenge here is that species interactions intrinsically vary in space and time @Poisot2015SpeWhy --- in addition to systematic phenological shifts, there is intrinsic year-to-year variation in the structure of empirical pollination networks @Alarcon2008YeaVar. Therefore we need a spatiotemporally explicit approach to understand the present composition of interaction networks and how they are changing @Strydom2021RoaPre. Forecasting the rewiring of networks as their species shift under different climate projections (and understanding how this rewiring affects ecosystem functioning, persistence, and the services ecosystems provide to people) is crucial to conservation strategies designed for uncertain climate futures, and the International Panel on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES) report on pollination identifies mapping pollinator systems as a necessary step toward addressing our gaps in knowledge @Potts2016AssessmentReport. However, spatially explicit predictions of network composition and remain rare because thorough spatial coverage of network composition and structure is very labor intensive @Strydom2021RoaPre. Despite this challenge, recent work has made progress toward integrating the Grinellian and Eltonian niches together @Gravel2019BriElt, enabling spatially explicit network predictions by combining a regional metaweb (all possible interactions across the regional species pool) with species distribution models to predict host composition across space @Dansereau2024SpatiallyExplicit. 

Here, we extend this framework to generate spatially explicit predictions of plant-pollinator network structure across the Southern Rocky Mountains and, crucially, to project how this structure will change over the rest of the 21st-century under potential climate scenarios. We use interaction data from 13 bumble bee species (_Bombus spp._), which have displayed particular sensitivity to climate warming across the globe @Kerr2015ClimateChange, and 157 angiosperm species to construct a regional metaweb composed of 697 known plant-pollinator interactions. We integrate this data with species distribution models to (1) produce spatiotemporally explicit predictions of the bumble bee and wildflower pollination network composition across the southern Rocky Mountains, and (2) identify where and when known interactions are likely to be lost under different climate scenarios. We find consistent upward elevational shifts in suitable habitat and substantial network rewiring across all scenarios, and large reduction in overlap between interacting species in stronger warming scenarios, albeit with considerable variation across species in the extent to which they gain or lose overlap with pollination partners. By quantifying the "vertical disassembly" of these networks, these projections provide a predictive baseline for monitoring change and can guide monitoring and conservation strategies.

