=== Shifting range overlap among interacting species

In @overlap-change\A, we show the density of the relative range overlap for all of the species each bumble bee interacts with in the moderate warming scenario (SSP 2-4.5) across each future time-period. In general we see decline in the median overlap for each bumble bee species, but there is conserable variation across the many plant species each bee interacts with.  

For each species $s$, we compute the range area that overlaps across each species $s$ interacts with, and from those values compute the median, resulting in a single value for each species. We refer to the case where we compute range overlap for each bee species $s$ as the _bee perspective_, and each plant species $s$ as the _plant perspective_. The distribution of the median change in range overlap from both the bee and plant perspectives are shown in @overlap-change\B (right) for each time-period and climate scenario, aggregated for each bee species in the top panel, and each plant species in the bottom panel. For example, this means each data-point in box-and-whisker plots for SSP 2-4.5 in the top panel of @overlap-change\B is derived from the the median value of the density for each bee in the corresponding time-period. 

For both sets of species (bee and plants), we see a very slight increase in overlap during the earliest time-period (2021-2040), with subsequent decrease in overlap for moderate and extreme climate scenarios (SSP 2-4.5 and 3-7.0), and relative stability for the mild warming scenario (SSP 1-2.6). From the bee perspective, in the moderate and extreme warming case, we see a large decline in range overlap, with a 25% decline relative to the baseline by 2100 in SSP 2-4.5, and a 40% decline by the end of the century for bee species in SSP 3-7.0. 

From the plant perspective, there is still a general pattern of decline in moderate and extreme climate scenarios, but there are also a considerable amount of number of plant outlier species, all on the upper end of increasing overlap. This corresponds to species "moving in" to the system at high levels as their range expands into the southern Rocky Mountains. For example, consider the labeled points in @overlap-change\B: _Ipomopsis aggregata_ already has a widespread range, but is projected to make large range gains in the northwest arid plains, along with many bee species (@range-shift)._Taraxacum officinale_, the common dandelion, is naturalized in temperate climates of North America, and expected to gain much range in the western part of the extent in the high-elevation arid grasslands. _Asclepias tuberrosa_ has limited distribution in the Front Range, but is widespread in the southwestern United States, including the south west of the region of interest. It is projected to gain considerable range in the southwestern foothills and at higher elevations in the east. _Asclepias asperula_ is already widespread in the south and expected to move northward. Across time-periods and climate scenarios, the members of the genus _Asclepias_ (milkweeds) in this study, _A. tuberosa_, _A. asperula_, and _A. speciosa_ consistently have the highest overlap relative to baseline.   

Despite the general trend of overlap decline, this variation points to a common feature of many ecosystems under projections of climate change, which is some species end up "winners", and some end up "losers".

