By combining in-situ interaction data with community science occurrence records and raster projections of bioclimatic variables, we are able to predict the contemporary ranges of the _Bombus_ pollination metaweb, and project the future range shifts of each species, and quantify the degree of spatial rewiring that this network will face over the remainder of the 21st century under different climate scenarios. We found consistent upward elevational range shifts under all scenarios, but with shifts being contained to around 150-250 meters upward by 2021-2040 under SSP 1-2.6, while suitable ranges continued to move further upward over the rest of the century under more extreme warming scenarios. We identified that there the foothills of the southern Rocky Mountains as a hotspot for interaction loss, with nearly an order of magnitude more interactions expected to be lost than gained in the locations with the most extreme change, suggesting vertical disassembly of this network may not be compensated by colonization by new species. The projected decline in median range overlap poses a significant threat to the robustness of these networks. Under both moderate and extreme warming scenarios there is considerable expected decline in the size of median range overlap by the end of the century (30-40% in SSP 3-7.0) from the perspective of both bumble bees and their pollinators. While some species emerge as climate "winners", the proportion of winners declines with increasing amounts of warming.   

It is essential to remember these projections are based on suitability based on bioclimatic variables, which are not, alone, the determinant of future distribution and abundance of species @Thomas2010ClimateClimate. There are numerous factors that are required for species to track their suitable climatic conditions. There are abiotic effects not directly accounted for here: for example the availability of oxygen (for bees) and carbon dioxide (for plants) is not directly considered in bioclimatic variables, and species may have physiological requirements that cannot be met where the climatic conditions of temperature and precipitation are most suitable @Jacobsen2020DilemmaAltitudinal. Additionally, high elevations are subject to more extreme winds, and the potential for frost, which both could damage plants and inhibit their reproduction @Steltzer2009BiologicalConsequences. 

Further, biotic effects also impact the ability of species to track their ranges. It is thought that the relative sparsity of pollinaters at high altitudes plant reproduction in alpine environments @Totland1993PollinationAlpine, although the more intense winds found at higher altitudes can substitute for animal pollination in some species @Totland2001PollenLimitation. There is also the impact of the limited dispersal capacity for some insects --- @Pyke2016EffectsClimate found upward shifts in the same system (bumble bees at RMBL field sites), but not enough to track the average temperature of their range 30 years prior @Pyke1982LocalGeographic. The reshuffling of ranges also will affect interactions besides plant-pollinator mutualisms: competition with newly arriving species has the potential to disrupt existing community structure. Even absent clear competitive advantages for some species, the ability of species to invade (or resist invasion) may be contigent on the order of arrival of species as priority effects are the primary factor in community assembly @Song2021UntanglingComplexity.

Therefore, our results predicting species and interaction richness into the future represent a "best-case" where species are fully capable of tracking their ranges. Rather than treating these as definitive forecasts of plant-pollinator network change, we believe these results provide guidelines for prioritizing further research into what species and particular interactions are expected to undergo the most change, and what the impact of this change on species diversity and persistence will be. For example, these projections identify which and where pairs of species expected to co-occur for the first time, which provides both a list of species to use models to predict if pollination interactions between these species are biologically feasible @Strydom2021RoaPre, but also spatial targets to validate these predicitons. This is essential to meet the guidelines from the International Panel on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES), which highlights mapping pollination as one of the necessary directions for addressing knowledge gaps in our understanding of plant-pollinator systems @Potts2016AssessmentReport.

Experimental conditions are necessary to confidently assess the ecological consequences of projected changes in network composition on species diversity, experimental systems @HilleRisLambers2013HowWill, but the full scope of all possible changes in these systems would prove impractical for rigorous experiment. Therefore the framework presented here can provide projected impacts that can guide these experiments toward testing the consequences of the changes that are most likely to be realized in the real world. Future work on developing mechanistic species distribution models to directly incorporate species physiological limits into range shift projections, but these models are very data hungry and thus benefit from work like this to prioritize data collection on species' physiological response to expected change.


We have demonstrated how species distribution modelling can be combinted with in-situ interaction surveys to generate spatially explicit projections of network structure to map the rewiring of plant-pollinator networks. Developing a spatiotemporally explicit theory of species interaction networks is essential for understanding and mitigating the consequences of climate change on these systems and the services they provide people @Strydom2021RoaPre. In addition to guidance for future experimentation, spatially explicit projections of network composition and change can guide where future monitoring efforts will be most fruitful, such that they can provide the most information possible to detect and attribute change @Gonzalez2023FraDet, and make better decisions to manage and mitigate the negative consequences of this change in these systems @Chapman2023BriAda. This work is essential to guide future long-term monitoring programs of plant-pollinator interactions, which can then collect data for shorter-term forecasts to better enable adaptive management and conservation @Dietze2018IteNea. Together, this would enable a multi-scale synthesis of biogeographic scale prediction of species interaction network composition (as done here) with process-based models of the dynamics of abudance in plant-pollinator communities @Valdovinos2019MutNet, which would serve to aid both conservation and better scientific understanding of the ecology and evolution of plant-pollinator mutualisms, and better mitigate the consequences of plant-pollinator rewiring in a warming world. 

